<TITLE> Dalai Lama urges Tibet hunger strikers to end fast </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Aug 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Dalai Lama appealed on Tuesday to 14 Tibetans to end a hunger strike, saying their action was "highly commendable" but sacrificing more Tibetan lives was unlikely to make China yield to their demands. The Tibetans, on their 31st day of fasting in New Delhi, have made several demands to China including that Beijing provide evidence that the Panchen Lama -- who they believe to be their second highest spiritual leader -- is alive. Tibetan activists accuse the Chinese government of being behind the disappearance of the boy, who was six years old when he went missing in 1995. Beijing has denied it is holding him. "The present indefinite hunger strike that you have undertaken with such unwavering courage and determination for the Tibetan cause ... is highly commendable and admirable," the spiritual leader said in a statement. "Nevertheless such an action is not only a form of violence ... but also simply sacrificing the lives of more Tibetan people is not likely to bring the positive results we seek." The Dalai Lama added that the hardships already endured by the hunger strikers, who are surviving on limited amounts of water, had fulfilled the key objective of gaining publicity. But representatives of the hunger strikers -- the oldest of which is 75 years old -- said despite their spiritual leader's appeal, the strike would continue and a mass protest involving thousands of supporters would take place in New Delhi on Wednesday. The fasting Tibetans want China to prove that imprisoned Tibetans, including activist Tulku Tenzin Delek who has been jailed for life, were given fair trials. They also want proof that Tibetans enjoy human rights and that new railway lines being built by China in the region are helping Tibet's development and not just bringing in more Chinese people to destroy the local culture. Chinese troops marched into Tibet in 1950 and Beijing has since left its mark on traditional Tibetan society, closing monaste